00:05:40.911 --> 00:05:42.660
DANIEL BURKA: So the
way that we typically

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:45.680
see design and development
done at startups

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:48.800
is that you come up with
an idea, a hypothesis,

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:51.200
something that might be
really great for your product.

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:53.640
And then you build the
lightest weight version of it

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:55.880
that you can, you
know a simple V1.

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:57.930
You really boil it down.

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:00.790
Launch it into the wild,
measure the results,

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:04.385
learn from those results, and
then iterate around the circle.

00:06:04.385 --> 00:06:06.760
Also from our experience this
is actually not a great way

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:08.200
to operate as a startup.

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:11.072
And what really happens
in the real world is

00:06:11.072 --> 00:06:12.905
you frequently are
starting with a bad idea.

00:06:12.905 --> 00:06:13.624
And that's fine.

00:06:13.624 --> 00:06:15.540
I mean, that's the whole
point of a hypothesis

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:18.180
is something you're not sure
of that you want to test.

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:20.430
But then you spend a lot of
time actually building out

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:22.310
that idea, and this
invariably takes

00:06:22.310 --> 00:06:24.564
much longer than
you think it will.

00:06:24.564 --> 00:06:26.230
You've now invested
the time, and so you

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:27.563
feel like there's no going back.

00:06:27.563 --> 00:06:30.490
Aw, we better launch this
thing and see what happens.

00:06:30.490 --> 00:06:33.110
And where you're expecting to
have really nice statistics

00:06:33.110 --> 00:06:35.040
and learn whether or
not something works,

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:38.160
it's usually much muddier
than you hope it will be.

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:39.160
And what's that quote?

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.520
There's lies, damn
lies, and statistics.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:45.860
And then when you're supposed
to be iterating again,

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:48.110
you actually just move on
to the next shiny idea.

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:49.790
And your products
out in the while.

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:51.040
And it's gumming up the works.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:52.956
You've got all this code
now in your code base

00:06:52.956 --> 00:06:54.130
that you no longer want.

00:06:54.130 --> 00:06:57.100
It's really hard to
go back at that point.

00:06:57.100 --> 00:06:59.150
So we're trying to
do at Google Ventures

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:01.440
is we're trying to
shortcut that process.

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:05.435
Over the course of a week we
ideate and flesh out an idea,

00:07:05.435 --> 00:07:08.580
we prototype it,
and then we test it.

00:07:08.580 --> 00:07:11.525
And we call that a
five day design sprint.

