and building it,
and designing it.

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:01.910
But we've also found
it's critical to have

00:10:01.910 --> 00:10:05.450
the founder, the decision
makers, the people who really

00:10:05.450 --> 00:10:07.420
understand on the ground
how the product works,

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:10.027
and how customers are
interacting with it.

00:10:10.027 --> 00:10:12.110
We all need to work together,
because in this case

00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:14.500
understanding how you
sell coffee beans online,

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:16.350
it's actually not
straightforward.

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.840
I didn't know how to do it
heading into the sprint.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:20.750
And so another thing
that we do on day one

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:23.117
is to look at things
out in the world

00:10:23.117 --> 00:10:24.950
and see if we can find
interesting patterns.

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:27.590
So we look at a bunch of
successful coffee websites,

00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:29.750
and we saw this
pattern right away

00:10:29.750 --> 00:10:33.190
that coffee is organized
quite commonly by region.

00:10:33.190 --> 00:10:34.430
So you can see it here.

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:35.780
Latin America, Africa.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:38.340
Here it is again,
Africa, the Americas.

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:39.540
Again here.

00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:41.335
This is the menu at Starbucks.

00:10:41.335 --> 00:10:43.710
Starbucks obviously knows a
thing or two about marketing.

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:46.020
You can see Guatemalan
coffee, Colombian.

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:47.812
And actually would you
guys raise your hand

00:10:47.812 --> 00:10:49.645
if you know the difference
between Guatemala

00:10:49.645 --> 00:10:50.680
and Colombian coffee.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:52.480
Does anyone here
know the difference?

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:53.250
OK.

00:10:53.250 --> 00:10:56.850
So a couple of you do
know, which is awesome.

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:58.670
But the rest of you
should not feel bad

00:10:58.670 --> 00:11:01.474
because as it turns out
normal humans don't get this.

00:11:01.474 --> 00:11:03.890
I mean, most of the people in
this room didn't understand.

00:11:03.890 --> 00:11:05.765
DANIEL BURKA: Heck, we
even had a guy came in

00:11:05.765 --> 00:11:07.797
for one of the user
studies who told us

00:11:07.797 --> 00:11:09.380
that he roasted his
own beans at home.

00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:11.671
So he's buying green beans,
he's roasting them himself,

00:11:11.671 --> 00:11:13.090
and then brewing his own coffee.

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:15.420
And even he sheepishly
admitted when we asked him.

00:11:15.420 --> 00:11:17.410
He's like, ah, when I
go to a cafe I never

00:11:17.410 --> 00:11:18.869
know really what
the difference is.

00:11:18.869 --> 00:11:21.368
JAKE KNAPP: We're like, dude,
like you roast your own beans.

00:11:21.368 --> 00:11:22.830
If you don't know nobody knows.

00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:23.810
And don't feel bad.

00:11:23.810 --> 00:11:26.529
So this is like a
big challenge for us.

00:11:26.529 --> 00:11:28.070
Like how should we
organize the beans

00:11:28.070 --> 00:11:30.940
and help people decide what
to have shipped to their home

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:33.182
if people don't
understand the regions?

00:11:33.182 --> 00:11:34.890
We asked Blue Bottle,
because they really

00:11:34.890 --> 00:11:36.550
wanted to take the
in-store experience

00:11:36.550 --> 00:11:37.500
and kind of bring it to the web.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:39.720
And we said, well, like how do
you guys do this in the store?

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:41.300
If somebody comes in and
they're looking at all

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:43.830
these brown paper bags, and
they want to buy some beans,

00:11:43.830 --> 00:11:45.140
how do you guide them
through that decision?

00:11:45.140 --> 00:11:46.723
And they said, oh,
well, when somebody

00:11:46.723 --> 00:11:49.372
asks for a suggestion we turn
around and say, how do you

00:11:49.372 --> 00:11:51.580
make your coffee at home,
because whether you make it

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:55.500
in a French press, or a Chemex,
or a drip machine that's

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:58.600
going to help us recommend
a great roast for you.

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:00.730
And I remember when
they said that.

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:02.710
I was looking at Daniel
and his eyes got big.

00:12:02.710 --> 00:12:05.180
And it was as if this
beam of inspiration

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:06.852
like shown in from outside.

00:12:06.852 --> 00:12:08.060
DANIEL BURKA: Just like that.

00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:08.690
Exactly.

00:12:08.690 --> 00:12:09.350
JAKE KNAPP: It was
just like that.

00:12:09.350 --> 00:12:10.950
This is a photograph,
so you know

00:12:10.950 --> 00:12:12.460
that it's exactly
how it happened.

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:16.074
And that kind of insight
actually only comes to us

00:12:16.074 --> 00:12:17.740
because we have the
whole team together.

00:12:17.740 --> 00:12:20.220
We have people who understand
every part of the product.

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:23.080
And that turns out to be true
across all kinds of companies.

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:25.230
So on the second day we've got a
bunch of insights from day one.

00:12:25.230 --> 00:12:27.380
We want to come up with a
bunch of different solutions

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:28.505
to compete with each other.

00:12:28.505 --> 00:12:31.615
So we don't just take one idea
and run with it off the bat.

00:12:31.615 --> 00:12:33.240
And the way we do
that is with drawing.

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:35.170
But I want to make
sure you understand

00:12:35.170 --> 00:12:36.670
we're not doing
group brainstorming.

00:12:36.670 --> 00:12:38.470
So we found that group
brainstorming just

00:12:38.470 --> 00:12:40.696
does not yield high
quality results.

00:12:40.696 --> 00:12:42.570
Instead what we want
are individuals spending

00:12:42.570 --> 00:12:46.300
a long time, so an hour, two
hours, sketching very detailed,

00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:48.250
very well thought
through, and very

00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:50.650
divergent opposing solutions.

00:12:50.650 --> 00:12:53.580
By the end of the day we've got
10, 12 different designs that

00:12:53.580 --> 00:12:56.080
are all very detailed, and
they compete with each other.

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:59.560
They can help us pick from a
number of different options.

00:12:59.560 --> 00:13:01.490
That choice though
is not so easy.

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:04.222
And if any of you know, you
may have been in meetings

00:13:04.222 --> 00:13:05.930
like this where you're
kind of discussing

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:07.513
things, and
intellectualizing, and try

00:13:07.513 --> 00:13:09.460
to imagine like
which solution will

00:13:09.460 --> 00:13:11.310
work best in the real world.

00:13:11.310 --> 00:13:15.200
And, you know, we want to get
some wisdom from everybody,

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:17.420
but we also don't want
design by committee.

00:13:17.420 --> 00:13:20.450
And the way we kind of hack
the decision making process

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:22.600
is something we call
weighted voting.

00:13:22.600 --> 00:13:25.280
So first we'll give
everybody as many

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:28.360
as they want of these
little blue stickers.

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:31.750
And you put the stickers by the
parts of ideas that you like.

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:33.510
So very quickly
we get a heat map

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:35.430
on all these
drawings of the parts

00:13:35.430 --> 00:13:37.630
of the ideas that work best.

00:13:37.630 --> 00:13:40.670
Next, we talk to the company
about how they make decisions.

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:43.744
In this case, James the
founder, Katie the COO,

00:13:43.744 --> 00:13:45.410
they're the ones who
really need to make

00:13:45.410 --> 00:13:47.140
the call on which
prototype we build,

00:13:47.140 --> 00:13:49.430
on which design goes forward.

00:13:49.430 --> 00:13:52.460
So we give them a number
of these very big red dots,

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:54.190
and they have a
limited quantity.

00:13:54.190 --> 00:13:56.220
In this case they
pick three designs.

00:13:56.220 --> 00:13:58.890
So first there's this idea
of recreating the cafe.

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:01.715
So what if we literally took
the interior design of a Blue

00:14:01.715 --> 00:14:05.110
Bottle Cafe and made a
website that looked that way?

00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:06.750
The second idea is storytelling.

00:14:06.750 --> 00:14:08.350
Over the last day
and a half we've

00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:10.760
heard all of this great
knowledge and expertise

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:13.409
from talking to the
Blue Bottle folks,

00:14:13.409 --> 00:14:14.950
and we wonder what
happens if we just

00:14:14.950 --> 00:14:17.496
write a lot of that
stuff on the website.

00:14:17.496 --> 00:14:18.870
And then third,
there's that idea

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:22.830
of organizing beans by the way
you brew your coffee at home.

00:14:22.830 --> 00:14:24.830
Problem is we've got like
three different ideas,

00:14:24.830 --> 00:14:27.050
and we still have to
make a prototype, right?

00:14:27.050 --> 00:14:28.990
So we decided to
do, in this case,

00:14:28.990 --> 00:14:30.440
is what we call a Battle Royale.

00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:33.020
We're going to pit the three
prototypes against each other,

00:14:33.020 --> 00:14:35.600
and we're actually going
to build all three.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:37.315
Problem is, it's
already Thursday,

00:14:37.315 --> 00:14:39.820
and we only have one
day, and it seems

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:41.839
like there couldn't
possibly be enough time.

00:14:41.839 --> 00:14:43.380
DANIEL BURKA: So
we're going to build

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:44.787
three prototypes
in a single day.

00:14:44.787 --> 00:14:47.120
And we're not going to stay
up until 4:00 in the morning

00:14:47.120 --> 00:14:47.820
to do it.

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:51.610
We've got a few fancy tricks
in order to get there.

00:14:51.610 --> 00:14:53.930
The first, is that when we
were doing the sketching

00:14:53.930 --> 00:14:56.080
we were not just sketching
individual screens.

00:14:56.080 --> 00:14:59.600
We were sketching little
three step or four step flows.

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:01.684
So when we unpack the
ideas that we want to make,

00:15:01.684 --> 00:15:03.475
we're able to lay them
out in a storyboard.

00:15:03.475 --> 00:15:05.790
And this is, running
from the top,

00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:08.010
a storyboard of the
15 or 20 screens

00:15:08.010 --> 00:15:09.440
that a user will run through.

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:12.690
And we can just translate
those right onto the board.

00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:14.360
And then, as Jake
was saying earlier,

00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:16.120
when people were
doing the sketching

00:15:16.120 --> 00:15:17.660
they weren't BSing it.

00:15:17.660 --> 00:15:20.039
They were taking the
time to write real copy.

00:15:20.039 --> 00:15:21.830
They were putting where
the image might be,

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:24.920
where buttons might be, what
realistic micro copy there's

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:25.640
going to be.

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:28.130
And so we're able to just
take it from low fidelity

00:15:28.130 --> 00:15:31.270
and push it up to a
much higher fidelity.

00:15:31.270 --> 00:15:33.260
And to move to that
level of fidelity

00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:36.250
we actually choose
intelligent tools.

00:15:36.250 --> 00:15:38.850
And we're not working
in Photoshop generally.

00:15:38.850 --> 00:15:41.090
We often work in
Keynote for instance.

00:15:41.090 --> 00:15:44.220
This is a Keynote mock from
the Blue Bottle sprint.

00:15:44.220 --> 00:15:47.100
And we find it gives us that
Goldilocks level of fidelity.

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:49.860
It's neither so
basic that users know

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:51.810
that they're in a
prototype, but it's also

00:15:51.810 --> 00:15:54.800
not a good enough tool to do
production design where we're

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:56.830
spending a lot of
time polishing buttons

00:15:56.830 --> 00:15:59.190
and making everything
look exactly perfect.

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:02.735
We just want it to be good
enough to suspend disbelief.

00:16:02.735 --> 00:16:05.350
Keynote also has the advantage
that many people on the team

00:16:05.350 --> 00:16:06.290
can contribute to it.

00:16:06.290 --> 00:16:09.150
It's a low barrier
to entry design tool.

00:16:09.150 --> 00:16:11.070
And then we use things
like Keynotopia,

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:13.150
which is a little toolkit
that you can buy first

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:15.990
for Keynote to drag and drop
form elements into the mocks,

00:16:15.990 --> 00:16:18.890
so we're not redoing things
from scratch every time.

00:16:18.890 --> 00:16:21.440
It helps us move
really, really fast.

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:24.390
So in the end we've taken
these three different ideas

00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:26.780
and stitched together
15 to 20 step

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:29.020
prototypes of each one of them.

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:31.375
We've got this one under the
brand Telescope Coffee that

00:16:31.375 --> 00:16:34.530
is exploring the storytelling,
Lindon Alley Coffee, which

00:16:34.530 --> 00:16:36.370
is doing this kind of
skeumorphic version

00:16:36.370 --> 00:16:39.000
of the store, and Potting
Shed Coffee, which

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.100
is doing the filtering
interface for choosing coffees.

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:44.990
JAKE KNAPP: So it's Friday.

00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:48.720
And all week long this
fuse has been shortening.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:50.240
Now the bomb's going to go off.

00:16:50.240 --> 00:16:51.806
This is an amazing
drawing that I

00:16:51.806 --> 00:16:54.620
did in Keynote of an explosion.

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:57.437
But it's time for us to
find out which prototype

00:16:57.437 --> 00:16:58.270
is going to succeed.

00:16:58.270 --> 00:17:00.030
So we're doing the research.

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:01.630
And I want to talk
for just one second

00:17:01.630 --> 00:17:03.570
about research, because
a lot of companies,

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:07.150
both small and large, are
reluctant to do user research.

00:17:07.150 --> 00:17:09.869
And one big barrier
is that people

00:17:09.869 --> 00:17:13.150
feel like it's going to be
really hard and complicated.

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:15.824
People think, ah, I need to
have a behavioral psychologist

00:17:15.824 --> 00:17:17.240
on our team to run
the interviews,

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:19.834
and we need a special room
with like a one way mirror,

00:17:19.834 --> 00:17:21.619
and like a laser eye tracker.

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:24.390
And the reality is you
really don't need much.

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:26.250
This is our very fancy set up.

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:27.950
It's a laptop.

00:17:27.950 --> 00:17:30.610
And on the laptop we're
running Keynote full screen.

00:17:30.610 --> 00:17:32.530
We've pasted a browser
bar on the slide

00:17:32.530 --> 00:17:35.030
so it looks like you're
running a browser.

00:17:35.030 --> 00:17:36.600
And there's a webcam.

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:39.310
And using GoTo
Meeting, or Apple TV,

00:17:39.310 --> 00:17:42.030
will project into another room
so that the rest of the team

00:17:42.030 --> 00:17:44.170
can watch while one
person from our team

00:17:44.170 --> 00:17:46.280
conducts the interview
with these customers who

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:47.360
we've recruited.

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:49.510
So we do five one
on one interviews.

00:17:49.510 --> 00:17:52.080
And each interview we're
showing the customers the three

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:52.730
prototypes.

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:54.896
We're showing them the
existing Blue Bottle website,

00:17:54.896 --> 00:17:56.230
so we get kin d of a baseline.

00:17:56.230 --> 00:17:58.070
And what's great
about this is we

00:17:58.070 --> 00:18:01.391
get really good, really deep
data from just those five

00:18:01.391 --> 00:18:01.890
users.

00:18:01.890 --> 00:18:04.750
We'll hear a lot about why
things work and don't work.

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:07.110
We'll get a sense from
watching people react about

00:18:07.110 --> 00:18:11.230
whether they understand
parts of the designs.

00:18:11.230 --> 00:18:13.010
So the results of
our Battle Royale

00:18:13.010 --> 00:18:15.350
are clear at the end of Friday.

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:19.400
And this idea of recreating
the cafe totally bombed, which

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:20.860
is disappointing
to me personally

00:18:20.860 --> 00:18:23.040
because it's the
design I worked on.

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:24.680
But it's actually
really good news

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:26.600
if you're Blue Bottle,
because they didn't

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:29.930
have to build, and
launch, and then

00:18:29.930 --> 00:18:32.080
wait to get those
results from the wild.

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:34.350
And you remember that this
was an idea that we really

00:18:34.350 --> 00:18:36.070
liked before we tested it.

00:18:36.070 --> 00:18:36.730
So it's great.

00:18:36.730 --> 00:18:38.260
We dodged a bullet.

00:18:38.260 --> 00:18:40.750
And it turns out that both
this idea of storytelling

00:18:40.750 --> 00:18:43.930
and the idea of sorting
by how you brew at home

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:45.127
were very successful.

00:18:45.127 --> 00:18:47.460
And that's also kind of cool
because both of those ideas

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:49.194
were a bit risky.

00:18:49.194 --> 00:18:50.610
Putting a lot of
text on a website

00:18:50.610 --> 00:18:52.940
isn't what you suspect
will normally work.

00:18:52.940 --> 00:18:55.940
And nobody else was
organizing coffee in that way,

00:18:55.940 --> 00:18:57.870
so if they just
had one shot at it

00:18:57.870 --> 00:19:00.574
they might not have
taken those risks.

00:19:00.574 --> 00:19:02.740
Now they had the confidence
that these ideas worked,

00:19:02.740 --> 00:19:05.310
and they went ahead and did the
ship early, ship often thing.

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:07.700
And so they designed
the full site.

00:19:07.700 --> 00:19:09.870
And here's what it looks
like in the wild today.

00:19:09.870 --> 00:19:13.640
So you can see you organize the
coffee by how you brew at home.

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:15.870
And you might recognize
this from the sketches.

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:17.790
A lot of that copy
is still there.

00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:19.930
You see this really
long block of text.

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:22.450
And conventional wisdom, don't
put a lot of copy on the web.

00:19:22.450 --> 00:19:23.750
People aren't going to read it.

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:25.780
Turns out, we know that
it builds confidence

00:19:25.780 --> 00:19:27.670
that these guys
are legit and they

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:29.890
know a lot about the coffee.

00:19:29.890 --> 00:19:32.490
They launched this website,
and it did quite well.

00:19:32.490 --> 00:19:34.530
So they doubled the
time spent on site,

00:19:34.530 --> 00:19:37.280
and in turn they doubled their
sales growth, which is great.

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:38.530
That's exactly what
they were hoping

00:19:38.530 --> 00:19:40.300
for from this part
of their business.

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:43.087
But you may be thinking
like this is just a website.

00:19:43.087 --> 00:19:45.170
DANIEL BURKA: So we've
done these types of sprints

00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:46.450
with many different companies.

00:19:46.450 --> 00:19:47.600
Part of the reason
we chose Blue Bottle

00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:49.820
is because it's a pretty
simple story to tell,

00:19:49.820 --> 00:19:52.790
but it's also a pretty simple
app when you look at it.

00:19:52.790 --> 00:19:55.680
You know, everybody's designed
an e-commerce site before.

00:19:55.680 --> 00:19:58.210
We've done lots and lots of
mobile prototypes as well.

00:19:58.210 --> 00:19:59.860
This is an example
from a sprint we

00:19:59.860 --> 00:20:01.459
did with a company
called Cluster.

00:20:01.459 --> 00:20:03.250
So you can see we're
using a similar method

00:20:03.250 --> 00:20:06.380
to sketch it out,
similar ideation.

00:20:06.380 --> 00:20:10.120
Here we're designing in
Keynote, piecing it altogether,

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:12.740
and then we're dragging it into
an app called Flinto, which

00:20:12.740 --> 00:20:15.080
is an excellent mobile
prototyping tool, which

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:17.190
means that we can
get it onto device.

00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:21.120
And we've developed two
comps here in a single day.

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:23.161
As you can see,
they look and feel

00:20:23.161 --> 00:20:25.410
a lot like a real mobile
app, even though they're just

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:27.190
static images stitched together.

00:20:27.190 --> 00:20:28.940
They've got buttons
and transitions.

00:20:28.940 --> 00:20:31.180
The title bar stays still.

00:20:31.180 --> 00:20:32.804
It's good enough to
suspend disbelief

00:20:32.804 --> 00:20:34.720
so we can get really,
really valuable feedback

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:36.470
from the users.

00:20:36.470 --> 00:20:38.940
And the second brand,
same kind of idea,

00:20:38.940 --> 00:20:42.760
all put together
in a single day.

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:45.380
And the set up is really
similar for user studies too.

00:20:45.380 --> 00:20:47.520
Just a document camera
over top of the device.

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:51.121
And we have the person actually
