00:22:06.300 --> 00:22:09.010
And then the examples
I just gave you,

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:10.980
everything I've shown
you thus far has all

00:22:10.980 --> 00:22:12.570
been consumer stuff.

00:22:12.570 --> 00:22:15.020
And so it's easy to recruit
users for consumer things,

00:22:15.020 --> 00:22:17.760
because they're similar to
us, and there's lots of people

00:22:17.760 --> 00:22:19.660
all over the world who
fit that demographic.

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:22.220
But we've actually done work
with many different startups

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:23.220
in many different areas.

00:22:23.220 --> 00:22:27.470
We've recruited people like
geneticists and oncologists,

00:22:27.470 --> 00:22:30.160
woodworkers, truckers even
for one of the studies

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:33.710
that we did, and 80 other
companies across a wide variety

00:22:33.710 --> 00:22:36.100
of industries, everything
from small startups

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:38.370
to big enterprises.

00:22:38.370 --> 00:22:40.740
JAKE KNAPP: So we're
investing in these companies,

00:22:40.740 --> 00:22:42.420
and we want them
to be successful.

00:22:42.420 --> 00:22:44.336
We think this is an
excellent process for them

00:22:44.336 --> 00:22:46.729
to use to build
confidence quickly.

00:22:46.729 --> 00:22:49.270
And if you guys are interested
in running a sprint like this,

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:51.200
there's kind of three
key ideas that I

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:52.447
think you ought to remember.

00:22:52.447 --> 00:22:54.030
One of them is
creating time pressure.

00:22:54.030 --> 00:22:56.030
It turns out that you can
manufacture a deadline

00:22:56.030 --> 00:22:56.925
in a lot of ways.

00:22:56.925 --> 00:22:59.259
The second is getting
into a prototype mindset.

00:22:59.259 --> 00:23:01.800
And we try to figure out how to
build something high fidelity

00:23:01.800 --> 00:23:04.370
as quickly as possible, rather
than building something real.

00:23:04.370 --> 00:23:06.830
Just creating a
veneer of reality.

00:23:06.830 --> 00:23:09.800
And finally, getting in this
mode of doing quick research,

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:13.830
which really doesn't have
to be very complicated.

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:16.240
We hear this phrase a lot
around Silicon Valley,

00:23:16.240 --> 00:23:19.150
and I don't think it's
necessarily like a bad idea,

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:21.910
but we just want to edit it
a little bit, because what

00:23:21.910 --> 00:23:23.650
everybody really
ought to be doing

00:23:23.650 --> 00:23:25.850
is learning early
and learning often.

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:27.589
And when you do
it that way you'll

00:23:27.589 --> 00:23:30.130
find that you can really build
great products with a lot more

00:23:30.130 --> 00:23:36.500
confidence, or as my wife
would say, rent before you buy.

00:23:36.500 --> 00:23:38.530
If you guys are interested
in running sprints

00:23:38.530 --> 00:23:41.380
we've written a series
of blog posts about how

00:23:41.380 --> 00:23:43.410
to run your own
sprint, everything

00:23:43.410 --> 00:23:46.882
from the kind of pins you
should buy to all the way

00:23:46.882 --> 00:23:48.340
through to how to
run the research.

00:23:48.340 --> 00:23:51.684
If you go to gv.com/designsprint
you'll find the whole series.

00:23:51.684 --> 00:23:54.100
We've heard from a lot of
people who never actually talked

00:23:54.100 --> 00:23:58.040
to us, and successfully runned
sprints using that DIY guide.

00:23:58.040 --> 00:24:00.080
And thank you very much.

00:24:00.080 --> 00:24:03.290
That is the end
of the first talk.

00:24:03.290 --> 00:24:07.220
Now, you may have one lingering
question about design sprints,

00:24:07.220 --> 00:24:09.030
which is like if I
work at a big company,

00:24:09.030 --> 00:24:10.446
like this is great
at the startup,

00:24:10.446 --> 00:24:12.040
but how do I make this work?

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:14.720
And I actually created
the design sprint process

00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:15.800
when I worked at Google.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:17.520
And I ran a bunch
of different sprints

00:24:17.520 --> 00:24:19.020
with a bunch of
teams across Google.

00:24:19.020 --> 00:24:20.519
But I wasn't sure
if it could really

00:24:20.519 --> 00:24:24.660
stick in a large
organization, which Google is.

00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:29.380
Nadya Direkova is a staff
designer and design evangelist

00:24:29.380 --> 00:24:30.320
at Google.

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:34.750
And she's taken the design
process, made some hacks to it,

00:24:34.750 --> 00:24:37.050
made some hacks to
Google's culture,

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:39.690
and been able to do over
80 sprints on some really

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:41.320
awesome products.

00:24:41.320 --> 00:24:43.850
I'm very excited to
introduce you to Nadya.

00:24:43.850 --> 00:24:46.750
And she's going to tell you
how it's done at Google.

00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:49.557
So without further
ado, here's Nadya.

00:24:49.557 --> 00:24:50.640
NADYA DIREKOVA: Thank you.

00:24:55.930 --> 00:24:56.870
Thank you, Daniel.

00:24:56.870 --> 00:24:59.220
Thank you, Jake.

00:24:59.220 --> 00:25:01.420
I'm really excited
to be here today.

00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:04.880
I've been looking forward
to this because very rarely

00:25:04.880 --> 00:25:08.870
do we get a chance to talk about
how we do design at Google.

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:10.820
And with the design
sprints we have

00:25:10.820 --> 00:25:14.380
something that's
really cool and unique.

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:19.880
Is it cool and unique because
design matters for all of us.

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:22.940
And speed matters.

00:25:22.940 --> 00:25:25.560
If you're a startup up,
you're running out of money

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:27.350
as soon as you raise them.

00:25:27.350 --> 00:25:29.930
And if you're a
large company you

00:25:29.930 --> 00:25:32.190
might have a team
and a goal that

00:25:32.190 --> 00:25:34.410
is so large that by the
time that you meet it

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:36.750
it becomes obsolete.

00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:41.510
By combining speed and design
we are creating design sprints

00:25:41.510 --> 00:25:44.870
to help a number of products
advance their goals.

00:25:44.870 --> 00:25:48.090
That helps us avoid
wasting time, money,

00:25:48.090 --> 00:25:51.120
and precious ideas.

00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:52.690
It is true what Jake said.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:55.840
I have done 80 design sprints.

00:25:55.840 --> 00:25:58.180
And perhaps I should
warn you, it's

00:25:58.180 --> 00:25:59.920
an addictive way of working.

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:04.460
Once you start you don't know
where you're going to end up.

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:06.560
I have not done these
sprints by myself.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:08.710
In every case there's
been a talented team

00:26:08.710 --> 00:26:11.170
that worked with me
to compile their goals

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:14.580
and to decide how and
where they want to end up.

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:17.980
So today I want to share with
you some stories about sprint

00:26:17.980 --> 00:26:21.490
at Google X, sprints
at Google at scale,

00:26:21.490 --> 00:26:24.000
and I want to give you
five hacks about how

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.260
you might be able to
do your own sprints.

00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:31.030
Let's start with
Google X. As you know,

00:26:31.030 --> 00:26:33.980
X is the new product laboratory,
and we developed things

00:26:33.980 --> 00:26:35.660
like the self driving cars.

00:26:35.660 --> 00:26:38.640
That was also the first
large sprint that I did.

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:40.380
The team came to
me, and they said,

00:26:40.380 --> 00:26:42.840
we want to create a shared
vision of how this product can

00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:45.840
be not just an amazing
scientific discovery but also

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:48.320
an amazing product for people.

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:50.350
As I started talking
to them I realized

00:26:50.350 --> 00:26:55.220
that an interesting thing is
that by the nature of their job

00:26:55.220 --> 00:26:58.080
each of them are focused
on different time frames.

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:00.050
Some people are focused
on the short term,

00:27:00.050 --> 00:27:03.110
and some people are
focused on the long term.

00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:05.090
In addition, what
was going to be

00:27:05.090 --> 00:27:08.750
available for the team in terms
of technology and capacity

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:10.140
changes over time.

00:27:10.140 --> 00:27:14.480
So what's available today,
tomorrow, and in four years

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:16.220
from now really expands.

00:27:16.220 --> 00:27:20.150
The technology frontier for
anyone expands over time.

00:27:20.150 --> 00:27:22.730
So how do you create the
shared vision for something

00:27:22.730 --> 00:27:24.870
that changes so much,
and where people already

00:27:24.870 --> 00:27:27.300
perceive it in different ways?

00:27:27.300 --> 00:27:30.420
What we did is create
two teams in parallel.

00:27:30.420 --> 00:27:34.980
In five days we were able
to create even more output

00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:36.920
by sending one team
with requirements

00:27:36.920 --> 00:27:39.910
for working two years
from now, and another team

00:27:39.910 --> 00:27:42.730
working with requirements
for four years from now.

00:27:42.730 --> 00:27:45.840
They were able to create
really exciting vision videos,

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:48.910
and show the team kind of
like a postcard of what

00:27:48.910 --> 00:27:52.070
might be happening in the future
and help make better choices.

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:54.960
That was one week out of many,
but a very interesting week.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:01.500
One day I walked into
campus and I saw this.

00:28:01.500 --> 00:28:04.270
And I thought what is this?

00:28:04.270 --> 00:28:08.540
This is one of the
balloons for Project Loon.

00:28:08.540 --> 00:28:10.950
The team is sending
these balloons in the air

00:28:10.950 --> 00:28:14.120
in order to help
distribute internet

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:17.220
for parts of the world
that don't really get it.

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:19.180
It's an amazing project.

00:28:19.180 --> 00:28:21.240
It gives me a sense of wonder.

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:23.100
At the same time what
was really important

00:28:23.100 --> 00:28:25.520
for them to create
great antennas so

00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:27.560
the signal that's
sent from the air

00:28:27.560 --> 00:28:29.540
can be received on the ground.

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:33.560
So the talented design team at
the design kitchen at Google X

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:34.640
ran a design sprint.

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:36.290
They came together.

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:38.240
They explored different ideas.

00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:43.720
And they made prototypes,
like hardware prototypes,

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:47.720
like various different kinds
of antennas that they can test.

00:28:47.720 --> 00:28:50.540
What's interesting about it
is that if you put an antenna

00:28:50.540 --> 00:28:54.030
on a conference room table, you
cannot tell if it's too large,

00:28:54.030 --> 00:28:56.540
too small, or if
it's easy to install.

00:28:56.540 --> 00:28:58.670
It doesn't give you
a lot of information.

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:00.540
So you actually
have to try putting

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:03.160
the antennae on different
pieces of something

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:04.990
that kind of looks like a house.

00:29:04.990 --> 00:29:07.370
And, in fact, they built
a house mock up in order

00:29:07.370 --> 00:29:10.160
to be able to do that like that.

00:29:10.160 --> 00:29:11.670
How cool is that?

00:29:11.670 --> 00:29:13.390
If you go to your
team and say, let's

00:29:13.390 --> 00:29:15.180
build a house so we
can test our ideas,

00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:16.717
they might think you're crazy.

00:29:16.717 --> 00:29:18.300
But that might also
be the right thing

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:20.091
to do if you want to
test your idea if it's

00:29:20.091 --> 00:29:22.420
related to something like that.

00:29:22.420 --> 00:29:25.130
Glass is another team
that uses sprints

00:29:25.130 --> 00:29:27.300
internally as one
of the toolkits.

00:29:27.300 --> 00:29:30.540
But they also pioneered
the idea of design sprints

00:29:30.540 --> 00:29:33.010
for developers, for you guys.

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:36.290
So the Glass development
team invites developers

00:29:36.290 --> 00:29:38.610
to come and learn
about the platform.

00:29:38.610 --> 00:29:40.160
What are the design
requirements?

00:29:40.160 --> 00:29:42.280
How do you make
something good with this?

00:29:42.280 --> 00:29:44.680
They had a chance
to try the hardware,

00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:47.380
to come up with different
ideas, and quickly

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:51.410
put the ideas from a Post-it
into something that's

00:29:51.410 --> 00:29:52.760
like a functional prototype.

00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:54.430
It all happens in
about four hours.

00:29:54.430 --> 00:29:56.160
The sprint is not very long.

00:29:56.160 --> 00:29:57.910
And they logged their ideas.

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:00.240
And now they can see
what they've made.

00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:02.590
And they can get feedback too.

00:30:02.590 --> 00:30:03.690
Quick learning.

00:30:03.690 --> 00:30:06.180
Exciting experience.

00:30:06.180 --> 00:30:08.960
So you see how this works
pretty cool for a product

00:30:08.960 --> 00:30:11.780
lab like Google X. But
does it work at scale?

00:30:11.780 --> 00:30:14.940
If you have a huge team and a
huge goal how does it happen?

00:30:14.940 --> 00:30:16.510
Indeed, we have
found that sprints

00:30:16.510 --> 00:30:19.720
have become very popular with
teams across the company.

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:23.090
It's become one of the ways
in which the teams work,

00:30:23.090 --> 00:30:25.610
from Google Fiber to Hangouts.

00:30:25.610 --> 00:30:28.625
In fact, if you have used
Hangouts to call your mom

00:30:28.625 --> 00:30:31.940
please thank Jake over here.

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:34.180
The guy created the
idea of design sprints

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:37.850
at Google working with
team, and he used the sprint

00:30:37.850 --> 00:30:40.560
to create an early version
of what became Hangouts

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:42.790
as a product.

00:30:42.790 --> 00:30:44.590
The team that's
working on Hangouts

00:30:44.590 --> 00:30:48.900
is also using design sprints
to redesign and launch new UIs.

00:30:48.900 --> 00:30:53.070
So if that's not a design
feat, I don't know what is.

00:30:53.070 --> 00:30:57.110
The sprints here helped us
work with teams of four people,

00:30:57.110 --> 00:31:00.910
and up to teams of 175.

00:31:00.910 --> 00:31:01.810
I'm not kidding.

00:31:01.810 --> 00:31:03.380
We literally had
that many sprinters

00:31:03.380 --> 00:31:06.432
in a recent sprint
one month ago.

00:31:06.432 --> 00:31:08.390
I want to share a video
with you that gives you

00:31:08.390 --> 00:31:11.820
a sense of what it's like to
be a part of this large sprint,

00:31:11.820 --> 00:31:14.290
where teams are running
in parallel in order

00:31:14.290 --> 00:31:19.460
to meet goals in a very
shortened time frame.

