00:33:48.920 --> 00:33:51.470
will help you
compress your design

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:54.700
process from a large piece
to something that's short,

00:33:54.700 --> 00:33:56.140
a week or less.

00:33:56.140 --> 00:33:59.080
We're hoping that these
hacks will help you.

00:33:59.080 --> 00:34:04.270
First is to be aware that the
sprint is something to design.

00:34:04.270 --> 00:34:06.130
It's worth putting
the effort into it,

00:34:06.130 --> 00:34:09.080
and here's the workflow
for a typical sprint.

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:12.110
There's work before,
during, and after.

00:34:12.110 --> 00:34:13.800
Before the sprint
you want to make sure

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:16.179
that you're solving
the right problem.

00:34:16.179 --> 00:34:18.060
It doesn't matter if
you create something

00:34:18.060 --> 00:34:20.219
that no one wants
to use or it's not

00:34:20.219 --> 00:34:21.409
useful in your organization.

00:34:21.409 --> 00:34:23.420
So you need to focus
on a challenge.

00:34:23.420 --> 00:34:25.600
You want to create a team.

00:34:25.600 --> 00:34:27.600
Bring the right people together.

00:34:27.600 --> 00:34:30.600
Schedule the sprint so that it
makes sense and every minute

00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:32.020
is planned.

00:34:32.020 --> 00:34:35.650
During the sprint it's about
letting the teams experience

00:34:35.650 --> 00:34:39.050
the right set of design
methods and research methods.

00:34:39.050 --> 00:34:41.250
And it's about working
as fast as you can,

00:34:41.250 --> 00:34:43.320
helping resolve the
conflicts, looking

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:45.570
for that deeper insight.

00:34:45.570 --> 00:34:48.159
After the sprint it's
all about making sure

00:34:48.159 --> 00:34:50.659
that the results are
pointing towards launch.

00:34:50.659 --> 00:34:52.560
You want to be successful.

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:54.090
I want to draw
your attention here

00:34:54.090 --> 00:34:57.740
to how much effort is
involved before and after.

00:34:57.740 --> 00:34:59.919
Many people skip that
part, and they only

00:34:59.919 --> 00:35:01.335
focus on the middle
of the sprint.

00:35:01.335 --> 00:35:04.960
It's so exciting, let's just
run and make amazing things.

00:35:04.960 --> 00:35:07.080
You want to make sure
that you're prepared,

00:35:07.080 --> 00:35:09.820
and that you're pointing towards
launch before and after so

00:35:09.820 --> 00:35:13.800
that you can be successful
in order to create.

00:35:13.800 --> 00:35:16.440
Now, here's another hack.

00:35:16.440 --> 00:35:19.380
Because the design sprint is
a unique way of working we

00:35:19.380 --> 00:35:21.930
have also created a new role.

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:24.420
We call that the sprint master.

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:27.240
This is the person who's going
to be the CEO of the project

00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:30.480
and make sure for the duration
of the sprint everybody's

00:35:30.480 --> 00:35:33.300
working at an amazing pace.

00:35:33.300 --> 00:35:34.925
Now, this is not a
duck with a snorkel.

00:35:34.925 --> 00:35:37.200
It's a ninja.

00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:39.420
These people are awesome.

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:40.420
So here's Jin.

00:35:40.420 --> 00:35:43.290
He's the designer and
the sprint master.

00:35:43.290 --> 00:35:43.980
Here's Marty.

00:35:43.980 --> 00:35:46.485
He's a designer and
the sprint master.

00:35:46.485 --> 00:35:49.600
Ellen, Lauren, and Dave.

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:53.950
What they have in common is
that they're awesome designers,

00:35:53.950 --> 00:35:57.160
but they also are prepared
to be sprint masters,

00:35:57.160 --> 00:35:59.690
and they can take
their team and make

00:35:59.690 --> 00:36:03.300
them totally shocked in how
much they can achieve together.

00:36:03.300 --> 00:36:05.680
We found that by measuring
the satisfaction of sprints

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:07.370
that had and didn't
have trained sprint

00:36:07.370 --> 00:36:09.810
masters that the
second kind was better.

00:36:09.810 --> 00:36:11.860
People are more satisfied
with participating

00:36:11.860 --> 00:36:14.470
in a sprint that's well crafted.

00:36:14.470 --> 00:36:17.500
So the reason also that
sprint masters matter

00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:20.220
is that if you have a team
that's only sprinters,

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:22.550
the most predictable
outcome is that they end up

00:36:22.550 --> 00:36:24.882
in different directions.

00:36:24.882 --> 00:36:26.340
You need the sprint
master in order

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:29.310
to create the sense of a
common goal, of a shared

00:36:29.310 --> 00:36:32.025
goal, and a shared dream,
and let them run fast.

00:36:32.025 --> 00:36:35.050
And the sprint
master ensures that.

00:36:35.050 --> 00:36:37.670
Designing the team is another
and very interesting part

00:36:37.670 --> 00:36:38.740
of it.

00:36:38.740 --> 00:36:42.010
Now, you know from Jake that
working with designers, PMs,

00:36:42.010 --> 00:36:44.470
engineers, everyone
is really crucial.

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:46.380
What happens if you're
missing someone?

00:36:46.380 --> 00:36:49.180
Say you need to add the
researcher to your team

00:36:49.180 --> 00:36:50.870
because you don't have one.

00:36:50.870 --> 00:36:54.890
The sprint is an opportunity to
redefine who is on your team.

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:58.000
You can invite the researcher
from your larger organization,

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:00.670
or find someone
from the industry.

00:37:00.670 --> 00:37:02.460
No one wakes up
hoping that they're

00:37:02.460 --> 00:37:05.620
going to have a boring day in
which they do not contribute

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:08.890
decidedly anything
towards mankind.

00:37:08.890 --> 00:37:10.970
So when you invite
someone to a sprint

00:37:10.970 --> 00:37:12.790
they have a chance
to do something cool,

00:37:12.790 --> 00:37:14.310
and generally people say yes.

00:37:14.310 --> 00:37:17.080
I've been surprised on how many
people I've been able to invite

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:20.160
and enrich the team.

00:37:20.160 --> 00:37:22.380
Another hack is
about accountability.

00:37:22.380 --> 00:37:24.570
I put these brackets
here because I

00:37:24.570 --> 00:37:26.720
call these
accountability brackets.

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:29.170
It's about starting
and ending something.

00:37:29.170 --> 00:37:31.835
Just like in software you
don't start and forget

00:37:31.835 --> 00:37:34.380
to end something because it
doesn't compile if you don't

00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:37.070
have the right braces, these
accountability brackets

00:37:37.070 --> 00:37:39.510
help remind us about what
to do at the beginning

00:37:39.510 --> 00:37:40.670
and at the end.

00:37:40.670 --> 00:37:42.620
No matter what your
design processes is

00:37:42.620 --> 00:37:45.670
we recommend that you start
and end with user research.

00:37:45.670 --> 00:37:47.970
At the beginning you
want to open the bracket

00:37:47.970 --> 00:37:50.290
and talk to users,
learn about their needs.

00:37:50.290 --> 00:37:53.090
It is always amazing the
sense of empathy and discovery

00:37:53.090 --> 00:37:54.510
that you can get from that.

00:37:54.510 --> 00:37:58.140
Like the time Daniel kind of
